### Tab 2: Running Jobs (LIVE)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant React as Dashboard.jsx
    participant RQ as React Query
    participant API as GET /api/dashboard/running
    participant DB as msdb.dbo.sysjobactivity

    User->>React: Clicks "Running" tab
    React->>RQ: useQuery('runningJobs')
    Note over RQ: enabled: activeTab === 'running' ✅
    Note over RQ: refetchInterval: 15000ms 🔄
    RQ->>API: GET /api/dashboard/running
    API->>DB: Query sysjobactivity WHERE stop_execution_date IS NULL
    DB-->>API: Currently executing jobs
    API-->>RQ: JSON { count, jobs[] }
    RQ-->>React: Render running job cards

    Note over RQ: ⏱ 15 seconds later...
    RQ->>API: GET /api/dashboard/running (auto)
    API->>DB: Same query
    DB-->>API: Updated list (job may have finished or new one started)
    RQ-->>React: UI updates automatically
```

**When does it fetch?**

| Trigger | Fetches? | Why |
|---------|----------|-----|
| Click the "Running" tab | ✅ | `enabled` becomes `true`, triggers first fetch |
| Every 15 seconds while tab is active | ✅ | `refetchInterval: 15000` — **this is the live polling** |
| Click "Refresh" button | ✅ | Calls `refetchRunning()` manually |
| Switch to another tab | ❌ Stops | `enabled: false` → stops the 15s interval |
| A job starts/stops on the server | Shows on next poll | Within 0-15 seconds, the UI catches up |
| Browser tab regains focus | ❌ | `refetchOnWindowFocus: false` |

**What SQL does it run?**

Queries SQL Server Agent system tables directly:
```sql
SELECT j.name, ja.start_execution_date,
       DATEDIFF(MINUTE, ja.start_execution_date, GETDATE()) AS runningMinutes,
       js.step_name AS currentStepName
FROM msdb.dbo.sysjobactivity ja
JOIN msdb.dbo.sysjobs j ON ja.job_id = j.job_id
LEFT JOIN msdb.dbo.sysjobsteps js ON ...
WHERE ja.session_id = (SELECT MAX(session_id) FROM msdb.dbo.syssessions)
  AND ja.start_execution_date IS NOT NULL
  AND ja.stop_execution_date IS NULL       -- ← Still running!
  AND EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM dbo.Db_Job_Name cfg
              WHERE j.name LIKE cfg.job_name AND cfg.isEnabled = 1)
```

**Key conditions**:
- `start_execution_date IS NOT NULL` — job has started
- `stop_execution_date IS NULL` — job hasn't finished yet
- `session_id = MAX(session_id)` — only the current SQL Agent session
- `EXISTS (... Db_Job_Name ...)` — only jobs that match your configured job name patterns

**What data comes back?**

```
{
  count: 2,
  jobs: [{
    jobId: "ABC-123...",
    jobName: "Expense_Report_Audit_Kowa",
    clientName: "Kowa",
    startedAt: "2026-03-02T22:15:00",
    runningMinutes: 12,
    runningTime: "12m",
    currentStepName: "Extract Data",
    currentStepNumber: 3
  }]
}
```

